@node "INSTALL" "SN User-o-Meter v1.3 - Installation Procedures"
@toc "MAIN"
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  SN User-o-Meter v1.3 - Installation Procedures
└────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

 1  Run the included installation script either of the following
    two ways:

    a.  Type "Installer Install_UoM" from the Shell.

    b.  Click on the "Install_UoM" icon from Workbench.

 2  The installation script moves the required files to your specified
    location, including adding a CNet help file called "UOM."

    Note:  The help file loads up UoM in help mode.  You need to edit
           the file and make sure the path points to the correct location.

 3  I have included the full distribution archive of Sort v1.37 by R³diger
    Werner (Sort1_37.LHA).  You must install this sort program somewhere in
    your path.  It MUST be renamed to Sort137, however.  (I didn't want to
    overwrite the original sort, of course.)

 4  Add "UOM |{#0<path>UOM/SN_User-o-Meter}" to your bbsmenu under either
    "2; Available everywhere" or "3; Main prompt."  Modify your online
    menu(s)) to reflect the new addition.  Note that the above { is
    actually a control-Q command.

 5  Reload your bbstext/bbsmenu via CNet's Control Panel menu (option
    #3, "Text/menu reload  RAmiga-T" and you're all set!

 6  Add the following event:

    COMMAND:  RunARexx
    ARGS:     SN:UoM/SN_User-o-Meter C (provide correct path)
    PORT(S):  0 (or whatever your maintenance port is)
    TYPE:     Immediate - system idle or not
    MM/DD:    SSMTWTF
    TIME:     0 (or as close to midnight as possible)
    VALID:    1
    INTERVAL: 0
    ITERATE:  1

 7  If you're registered and want ALAS to check users as they log on,
    add the following line to your sys.welcome (or to _Added, _Begin or
    _End if you use SN's LoginConfig. :)  (The { is actually a CTRL-Q.)

    {#0<path>UOM/SN_User-o-Meter E}

 8  Login and type UOM from the main menu.

 9  The first thing that will happen is it will not find a configuration
    file.  This is normal.  It will then build one with the default
    settings and adapt itself to the path you ran it from.  Next, it'll
    automatically generate the first lists based on these default
    settings, so you can get an idea of what they look like.

10  Once at the main menu, you can go into the SysOp menu and configure
    the program to suit your needs.  NOTE:  The default settings require
    you to be level 31 to enter the SysOp menu.  If this is unacceptable,
    do it once first, then modify it to suit.

    Note:  In the unreg version it doesn't do a sanity check on what levels
           you put for Tools/Maint access, so it'll let you put 528 if you
           you enter it.  No one will be able to get IN, though, so don't be
           a smartass with it.  :)  It's fixed in the registered version
           and might get fixed in a later unreg version.

